        "text": "ἐπεκάθισεν ἐπ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " denotes the instantaneous, finished act which followed the spreading of the garments. To suppose (Ebrard, Olshausen), by way of justifying the reference to the animals, that we have here a loose form of speech, corresponding to the German phrase: he leaps from the horses, and such like, is out of the question, for the simple reason that no such ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σύλληψις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " can be assumed in the case of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 21:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", all the less so that, from this verse, it would appear that it was the ",
        "children": []
