  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Brought the ass.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The unbroken foal would be more easily subdued and guided when its mother was with it; such an addition to the ridden animal would usually be employed to carry the rider's luggage. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They put on them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐπάνω αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "their clothes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἱμάτια",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The two disciples, stripping off their heavy outer garments, abbas, or burnouses, put them as trappings on the two beasts, not knowing on which their Master meant to ride. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They set him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "thereon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐπάνω αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Thus the received text, and the Vulgate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Et eum desuper sedere fecerunt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But most modern editors, with great manuscriptural authority, read, \"he sat thereon.\" Some have taken the pronoun ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to refer to the beasts, and Alford supports the opinion by the common saying, \"The postilion rode on the horses,\" when, in fact, he rode only one of the pair. But the analogy is erroneous. The postilion really guides and controls both; but no one contends that Christ kept the mother ass in hand while mounted on the colt. The pronoun is more suitably referred to the garments, which formed a saddle for the Saviour, or housings and ornamental appendages (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He came invested with a certain dignity and pomp, yet in such humble guise as to discountenance all idea of temporal sovereignty. Matthew 21:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Set him thereon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But the preferable reading is ἐπεκάθισεν, he took his seat upon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A very great multitude (ὁ πλεῖστος ὄχλος)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The A. V. is wrong. The reference is not to the size, but to the proportionate part of the multitude which followed him. Hence Rev., correctly, The most part of the multitude.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Their garments (ἑαυτῶν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., \"their own garments.\" The disciples spread their garments on the beasts; the multitude strewed their own garments in the way. Dr. Edward Robinson, cited by Dr. Morison, speaking of the inhabitants of Bethlehem who had participated in the rebellion of 1834, says:\" At that time, when some of the inhabitants were already imprisoned, and all were in deep distress, Mr. Farrar, then English consul at Damascus, was on a visit to Jerusalem, and had rode out with Mr. Nicolayson to Solomon's Pools. On their return, as they rose the ascent to enter Bethlehem, hundreds of people, male and female, met them, imploring the consul to interfere in their behalf, and afford them his protection; and all at once, by a sort of simultaneous movement, they spread their garments in the way before the horses.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The variation of tenses is not preserved in the English versions. Spread their garments, aorist tense, denoting one definite act. Cut down, spread in the way, imperfects, denoting continued action. As Jesus advanced, they kept cutting branches and spreading them, and the multitude kept crying. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]